node.text: Brewer Jimbo turns the charm to 11 explore our cherry-powered barrel-aged stout. Most brewers only go to 10. Ours goes to 11.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Revolution Brewing on August 19, 2021. May be an image of drink.

node.text:
While we were absolutely thrilled to welcome V.S.O.J. back into our (and your) lives in July, we're quite nearly as excited to still have Strawberry Jacket to share with you for a little longer. The final product says so much about what our brewers and cellar team can do to explore the space between lumber, malt, and fruit.⁠
⁠
The core concept is a tricky landing to stick. Too much fruit and you're basically paying to wallpaper over the time and effort of barrel aging. Too little and you're not delivering on the promises of the name itself.⁠
⁠
There are far easier ways to get sweetness into a beer (beer being the end result of sugar water and all). But to get that lush, living character of real fruit? Only one real way to do that. So it's about math, blending, time, tasting, and even more math. ⁠
⁠
At the end, we're left with a medal-winning confluence of fresh, sweet strawberry melded inexorably to an assertive, deeply complex Barleywine. It manifests the kaleidoscopic fruit vividness of a 90s cereal commercial without ever letting you forget that this is a Barleywine and that it spent a goodly amount of time in American oak. ⁠
⁠
Starwberry Jacket isn't going to be around much longer. If nothing else, the employees of Revolution Brewing and their beer stipends will see to that. But for now, we've got it at the Taproom and Brewpub to share, and will be more than happy to tell you what we love about it. ⁠
⁠
Thanks to @mckbeer for the great 📸

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Revolution Brewing on August 19, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, standing and indoor.

node.text:
This is our Maintenance Manager Nick, tucked in among the new cartoner machine he worked so hard to help get running since he joined Revolution last November. So much of his work has been around our commitment to move from plastic packaging to paper. ⁠
⁠
Thanks to work by Nick and others on the production team, more than 90% of our production is going to be paper-bound. This investment has been a long time coming, and we're excited to bring you great beer in more sustainable package.⁠
⁠
Nick joined us from an industrial food manufacturer, and this is his first job in beer. When he's not holding cartons of things toward camera, he's hanging with his dog Hank (Hank is a girl) and going through the emotional rollercoaster that one goes through as a University of Illinois football fan. If you're a Ukranian Village resident, you can say "hi Nick" when you see him and leave him moderately confused for the rest of the day.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Revolution Brewing in Buckingham Fountain. May be an image of sky.

node.text:
The sunsets here just hit a little bit different during the summer. As we meander through the last bits of summer, it's a fun diversion to revisit those places so etched in civic memory that you forget you can just go see them in person. ⁠
⁠
Buckingham Fountain, at its central spot in Grant Park, was the original welcome mat laid out for visitors to our fine city. Yes, there's a huge and impressive robo-legume to the north that gets most of the press and television shots these days, but you can't forget the classics. The pink granite and Versailles-inflected design sticks out some in this hot-dog-and-Malört locale, and it's all the more memorable for the contrast. The combination of 150-foot bursts and merciful breeze has saved us on many a hot, sticky summer day. If it takes ornamental horses to deliver that refreshment, then we're all for these particular ornamental horses. ⁠
⁠
This colossal landmark somehow survives the winters we get, and that's a fine reminder for the rest of us. And when it's switched back on each spring, it's one of our surest signs that better days are ahead. ⁠
⁠
Also, it has wi-fi. Presumably for reasons.⁠
⁠
#FistCity

node.text:
When it came time to create a name and a label for our collaboration with @18thstreetbrewery for @barrelandflow, illustrator, comic artist, and professor John Jennings was more than up to the job. John's a former Midwesterner who has worked on projects for Marvel Comics, adapted the legendary works of Octavia E. Butler, and served as the creative force for Shop Talk.⁠
⁠
"The themes around this beer were connection, African-American culture, safe spaces in Black communities and how all of that would resonate in an Afro-centric beer festival," Jennings said. "I thought about the Afro-futurist perspective, the Great Migration, the history of the South Side of Chicago. Just all kinds of ideas tumbling around in our heads." ⁠
⁠
Eventually, he came to the idea of Shop Talk – the common shared language of particular professions – and applying that to both breweries and the common cultural (and pop-cultural) barbershop space. Shop talk is an understanding, a common language, and the latest about the latest. ⁠
⁠
"I liked the idea of reclaiming the idea of this COVID-affected space. Barbershops were originally a place of literal healing, doctoring as well as haircuts. The red on the barber pole represents a wrapped wound, and a place of healing," Jennings said. "It's also a space immune to class or age. Whether you're 8 or 80, paying 2 dollars or 200, everybody needs a haircut. The space becomes familiar, and takes on a life of its own."⁠
⁠
The nexus of conversation, healing, and community drives not just the name of this beer, but what Barrel & Flow is all about. At its best, Jennings said, the barbershop represents an interstitial, liminal space in the same way that a crossroads, depot, or airport does depending on your cultural signifier of choice.  At first, there's a discomfort as a new entry to an established space. But soon after, you belong. Things are cool. It's conversation, it's familiarity, it's community. ⁠
⁠
We're happy to have @johnjenningsart, 18th Street, @daybracey, and everyone at Barrel & Flow as part of our community. We hope Shop Talk, the festival, and everything is between is just the start of new spaces, new conversations, and a new way forward.
